>
<P N="2">2. He is for Nature <HI>co-e&s;&s;ential; I and my Fa|ther are one,</HI> &s;aith Chri&s;t, <HI>Joh.</HI> 10.30. So again. <HI>Joh.</HI> 1<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> 5, 7. <HI>There are three <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> record i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> heaven, the Father, the Word, and the Spirit, and the&s;e thre<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> are one.</HI> Mark here, they are one, <HI>Joh.</HI> 14.1. When <HI>Philip</HI> de&s;ires to &s;ee the Father, <HI>Sh<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">w at the Father, and it is enough;</HI> &s;ays Chri&s;t in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> and to ver&s;es, <HI>He that hath &s;een me, hath &s;een the Father:</HI> How &s;o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>For I am in the Father, and the Father is in me.</HI> So that you &s;ee Chri&s;t is more than meer Man, he's one with the Father. Oh, Sirs, he is the <GAP DESC="foreign">, the God-man, if you make the Son meer Man, you mu&s;t make the Father &s;o too.</P>
